WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.400
[Unknown]: IVM

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:09.200
[Amit Varma]: The most important lesson we learnt about economics in the 20th century was that economies

00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:14.280
[Amit Varma]: cannot be centrally planned. They run best when they are decentralized and largely free,

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:18.880
[Amit Varma]: with the state ensuring the rule of law and not much else. Millions of people, without

00:00:18.880 --> 00:00:23.200
[Amit Varma]: needing to coordinate with each other, make decisions in their self-interest that have

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:28.000
[Amit Varma]: the effect of leaving everybody better off. This was most famously articulated in Frederick

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.360
[Amit Varma]: Hayek's 1945 essay, The Use of Knowledge in Society, though the lesson took decades

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:38.600
[Amit Varma]: to filter down. The Soviet Union eventually collapsed, and even here in India, we eventually

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:44.720
[Amit Varma]: realized that Nehru's vision of a command-and-control planned economy was a flawed one. Our government

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:50.760
[Amit Varma]: stuck to that mindset though, as did our people. That's why every year, the nation tunes in

00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:56.980
[Amit Varma]: eagerly to listen to the finance minister summarize the budget for us. To find out what

00:00:56.980 --> 00:01:01.560
[Amit Varma]: our rulers, our lords and masters, have planned for us.

