[Amit Varma]: Srinath and Pranay Kotasthane, who are joining me remotely from Bengaluru. Pawan Pranay,

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:42.320
[Amit Varma]: welcome to the show.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:43.320
[Guest]: Thanks, a pleasure to be here.

00:02:43.320 --> 00:02:46.080
[Guest]: Thanks Amit, great to be here.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:50.080
[Amit Varma]: So before, you know, I don't really want to get started on a rant about how the concept

00:02:50.080 --> 00:02:54.840
[Amit Varma]: of a budget is so anachronistic and so socialist and, you know, in times when we should really

00:02:54.840 --> 00:03:00.080
[Amit Varma]: have moved away from all that. Leaving that aside, Pawan, could I ask you for a moment

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:04.680
[Amit Varma]: to sort of demystify for the listener, what a budget really is? What is the budget? What

00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:05.920
[Amit Varma]: is the government doing here?

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:12.120
[Guest]: Amit, the budget is a time where actually the Parliament's power shines through. As

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:17.640
[Guest]: powerful as a government of the day might be, the executive has to table how much it

00:03:17.640 --> 00:03:23.120
[Guest]: plans to spend over the next year in front of the Parliament. So therefore, subject itself

00:03:23.120 --> 00:03:29.480
[Guest]: to some form of scrutiny and some amount of oxygen and sunlight before it can go about

00:03:29.480 --> 00:03:34.800
[Guest]: and do all the nasty things that governments do in their various hidey holes and corners.

00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:39.560
[Guest]: So the budget is an exercise where the finance minister comes out and tables what they'll

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:47.040
[Guest]: be doing. And this time, the government of India will be spending about 24.4 lakh crore

00:03:47.040 --> 00:03:55.560
[Guest]: rupees, that's 24.4 trillion rupees, that's 18,000 rupees per Indian. And you know, it's

00:03:55.560 --> 00:04:02.960
[Guest]: about 12 to 13% of India's GDP. So that's what's on the table.

00:04:02.960 --> 00:04:05.440
[Amit Varma]: So help me make some sense of these numbers.

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:11.080
[Guest]: Okay, so let's say that the government of India's budget is 100 rupees. Okay, so that

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:17.320
[Guest]: number is 24.4 trillion right now, which sounds obscenely high. So the, you know, none of

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:24.520
[Guest]: us have human intuition about 24.4 trillion rupees. So supposing it's 100 rupees, the

00:04:24.520 --> 00:04:31.680
[Guest]: government makes about 56 to about 60 rupees from tax revenues coming in. This is the government

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:37.600
[Guest]: of India's share of the GST, the government of India's share of income taxes, of a whole

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:45.280
[Guest]: host of taxes. Another 10 to 15 rupees comes from non tax revenues, right? This is when

00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:52.640
[Guest]: the government decides to sell off coal, through various auctions, sale of spectrum, or if

00:04:52.640 --> 00:04:57.920
[Guest]: the government decides to, you know, divest its share of various national companies that

00:04:57.920 --> 00:05:05.040
[Guest]: we have. So altogether, the government makes about, this all adds up to about 70 rupees

00:05:05.040 --> 00:05:10.280
[Guest]: roughly. And then you know, there are small things like the recovery of loans, some receipts

00:05:10.280 --> 00:05:17.200
[Guest]: and so on. So altogether, the government makes about 74 to 75 rupees, the remaining 25 rupees

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:24.080
[Guest]: is all borrowed. Okay, so that's how the number adds up to 100. And on the spending side,

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:29.080
[Guest]: again, it spends on things on its own. You know, there are core functions of the government

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:34.520
[Guest]: of India, which only it is supposed to do under the constitution like defense, external

00:05:34.520 --> 00:05:39.720
[Guest]: affairs and so on. But it also spends on things that state and local governments have to do

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:48.800
[Guest]: from agriculture to health to a lot of other sectors. So all of this expenditure also comes

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:54.840
[Guest]: to about 77 rupees, and the remaining 23 rupees goes back to just paying interest, right.

00:05:54.840 --> 00:06:00.520
[Guest]: And so this is something that, you know, if you're a corporation, or an individual, if

00:06:00.520 --> 00:06:04.960
[Guest]: you're doing this, it sounds ridiculous, but governments seem to get away with it.

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:09.360
[Amit Varma]: And when sort of, you know, I was following social media today, and there was the and

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:13.800
[Amit Varma]: obviously, we the middle class people on social media, or even better than middle class people

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:17.760
[Amit Varma]: on social media, tend to sort of look at our own interests. And there's been a lot of talk

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:22.160
[Amit Varma]: about this cess and that cess and the cess is constantly going up. I know, it's a pet

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:27.200
[Amit Varma]: peeve of yours, Pranay. Can you tell me a little bit more about the cesses in this budget?

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:28.920
[Amit Varma]: And are they really necessary?

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:36.680
[Guest]: Yeah, Amit, so the government has increased the cess from 3% to 4%. And the cess basically

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:43.480
[Guest]: is a charge, which is levied for a specific purpose. So in this case, the government has

00:06:43.480 --> 00:06:50.040
[Guest]: levied increased the surcharge for health and education. So what the government is basically

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:56.400
[Guest]: saying is that, hey, I was not able to spend on health and education earlier. Now, if you

00:06:56.400 --> 00:07:02.440
[Guest]: give me more money, and for that, I'm going to introduce this new surcharge and increase

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:07.960
[Guest]: it by 1%. If you give me this money, I will be able to spend it on health and education.

00:07:07.960 --> 00:07:13.960
[Guest]: Now, my question is that, wasn't the government supposed to do that in the first place through

00:07:13.960 --> 00:07:20.600
[Guest]: the taxes that it has collected? Wasn't the first charge on taxes meant for critical areas

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:26.200
[Guest]: like health and education? So by increasing this cess, the government is admitting that

00:07:26.200 --> 00:07:32.120
[Guest]: it was perhaps wasting money on some other things that it was not supposed to. And now

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:37.680
[Guest]: it is forced to introduce a special charge so that it can do things on critical areas

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:39.360
[Guest]: like health and education.

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:44.840
[Amit Varma]: And Pranay, is there actually a way to keep track of whether these cesses are being used

00:07:44.840 --> 00:07:49.480
[Amit Varma]: for what they are supposed to be used for? And a sort of a larger question and something

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:54.000
[Amit Varma]: which a lot of people wonder about that, you know, quite apart from the budget being a

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:00.120
[Amit Varma]: statement of accounts once a year, and so on and so forth. Is there any way for taxpayers

00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:04.080
[Amit Varma]: to actually and by taxpayers, I don't just mean income taxpayers, every single Indian

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:07.960
[Amit Varma]: is a taxpayer in some way or the other, of taxpayers to kind of keep track of what the

00:08:07.960 --> 00:08:09.680
[Guest]: government is doing with their money?

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:16.760
[Guest]: Yeah. So a good source for that is something, there is something called standing committees.

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:22.960
[Guest]: So standing committees are basically parliamentary oversight over the executive. So what happens

00:08:22.960 --> 00:08:27.900
[Guest]: is there are very good reports which come out by the standing committee where the parliamentary

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:34.960
[Guest]: committee meets each of these executive departments and tries to take a stock of how was the money

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:40.720
[Guest]: used? How was it utilized? Where was it not spent? So those are good sources to know about

00:08:40.720 --> 00:08:53.360
[Guest]: how the money is utilized. Besides that, on specific programs like NREGA or NHM, National

00:08:53.360 --> 00:08:58.680
[Guest]: Health Mission, etc., there are dedicated websites where they have tried to put information

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:03.360
[Guest]: about how the money has been utilized over the year. So those are other places where

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:06.920
[Guest]: people can see how the money is being utilized.

00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:13.960
[Guest]: Amit, I want to come in here a little. And, you know, money is usually fungible. So when

00:09:13.960 --> 00:09:19.000
[Guest]: we talk about cessus and how they're being utilized, the reality of it is that the government

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:25.120
[Guest]: spends on many nasty things, including, say, keeping the Air India afloat or keeping other

00:09:25.120 --> 00:09:30.800
[Guest]: public sector units afloat. Now, if the government were actually being honest, maybe they should

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:37.240
[Guest]: call it an Air India cess or keep Air India flying cess and then charge that to the people.

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:43.440
[Guest]: But they don't want to. World over, you have problems where people use a lottery and say

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:49.800
[Guest]: that, yes, this lottery money that the government is running will be kept entirely for education.

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:52.400
[Guest]: But ultimately, all money is fungible.

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:56.680
[Amit Varma]: I think, in fact, there should be a bloated bureaucracy cess. But my next question to

00:09:56.680 --> 00:10:01.560
[Amit Varma]: you, Pawan, is when you were sort of deconstructing what the actual budget is, you pointed out

00:10:01.560 --> 00:10:06.280
[Amit Varma]: that let's say out of 100 percent, you know, if the budget is 100 rupees, 74 rupees is

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:11.040
[Amit Varma]: actually raised through taxes and blah, blah, blah. And the remaining 25 percent or so is

00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:18.520
[Amit Varma]: actually borrowed money, which presumably is a fiscal deficit. How important is a fiscal

00:10:18.520 --> 00:10:21.840
[Amit Varma]: deficit? And what does this budget do to address it?

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:31.240
[Guest]: OK, so in context, in India, the financial crisis and the time around the financial crisis

00:10:31.240 --> 00:10:36.920
[Guest]: was really bad for the country, not because of the crisis as such, but because of other

00:10:36.920 --> 00:10:42.560
[Guest]: things that happened here, which included the universalization of NREGA, the latest

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:48.040
[Guest]: pay commission coming and hitting people, you know, multiple things combined.

00:10:48.040 --> 00:10:53.240
[Guest]: What started happening was the government started borrowing about six percent or so

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:59.560
[Guest]: of GDP, rather that the expenditure of the government of India became that much higher

00:10:59.560 --> 00:11:05.240
[Guest]: compared to what it was earning. And that became so high.

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:11.680
[Guest]: And once a government starts borrowing so recklessly, the cost of borrowing goes up.

00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:17.120
[Guest]: So there are a few market mechanisms by which the governments will have to start feeling

00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:26.480
[Guest]: the squeeze. And from around 2011 or so, there has been this long but slow process of trying

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:33.320
[Guest]: to have the government of India borrow slightly less each year, because, you know, bureaucracies

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:38.880
[Guest]: being what they are, it's very hard for governments to just slash funding across the board very

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:42.240
[Guest]: easily. So they've been trying to reduce this over time.

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:50.920
[Guest]: So now the fiscal deficit last year stands between 3.5 and 3.7 percent of GDP. Now, this

00:11:50.920 --> 00:11:55.280
[Guest]: again, because it's a small percentage number, it doesn't sound like much, but every one

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:59.200
[Guest]: percent of GDP is about 18 to 19 trillion rupees.

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:03.720
[Guest]: So that's about, you know, 250 something billion dollars or so.

00:12:03.720 --> 00:12:09.520
[Guest]: So now when we're talking about this, even 0.1 percent of the fiscal deficit is quite

00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:15.360
[Guest]: high. You know, 0.1 percent is 18,000, 19,000 crores, 0.1 percent is 3 billion dollars.

00:12:15.360 --> 00:12:23.520
[Guest]: So that's the number that we are playing with. Now, in general, it's not a bad idea to borrow

00:12:23.520 --> 00:12:26.960
[Guest]: money if you are trying to invest it in the future, right?

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:32.520
[Guest]: So if, Amit, you were borrowing money because you wanted to invest in an office, invest

00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:38.280
[Guest]: in, you know, a setup which would give you a return over many years, you know, somebody

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:44.400
[Guest]: might give you the loan for one. But if you were taking a loan to replace your salary

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:49.880
[Guest]: to take care of day to day expenses, then the bank would laugh at you. Unfortunately,

00:12:49.880 --> 00:12:56.920
[Guest]: what's happening in India is that within the fiscal deficit, there is a large revenue deficit,

00:12:56.920 --> 00:13:00.980
[Guest]: where the government is not able to meet its revenue, day to day expenditures from salaries

00:13:00.980 --> 00:13:06.320
[Guest]: to other things. And that is not being met right now by taxes. So the government of India

00:13:06.320 --> 00:13:11.120
[Guest]: is that profligate. Just for context, our state governments are much, much better at

00:13:11.120 --> 00:13:17.280
[Guest]: this. They don't run revenue deficits, but surpluses. They by and large borrow to invest.

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:19.400
[Amit Varma]: How are the incentives different?

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:24.560
[Guest]: I think with the state governments, the central government, the union government gets to have

00:13:24.560 --> 00:13:29.240
[Guest]: one role. And I think states, by and large, somehow stuck to this discipline a little

00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:34.960
[Guest]: better so far. But the central government, look, you have this thing called the Fiscal

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:40.240
[Guest]: Responsibility and Budget Management Act, the FRBM, which tries to bring in some controls

00:13:40.240 --> 00:13:47.020
[Guest]: of discipline where, you know, it is not as simple as the government just printing new

00:13:47.020 --> 00:13:53.240
[Guest]: notes, but the RBI comes in and steps in a few ways to give it some accountability. But,

00:13:53.240 --> 00:13:56.360
[Guest]: you know, this is not yet working as well as it should.

00:13:56.360 --> 00:14:00.680
[Amit Varma]: And has this budget taken any steps to making the fiscal deficit less or treating it as

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:01.680
[Amit Varma]: a problem?

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:08.600
[Guest]: No, in fact, it's one of those cases of shifting goalposts. Every year, there is a new reason

00:14:08.600 --> 00:14:13.240
[Guest]: for why the fiscal deficit should not get reduced. Right now, I think the talk of it

00:14:13.240 --> 00:14:19.960
[Guest]: is how you don't have the private sector investing in the economy because there is a huge amount

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:24.240
[Guest]: of private debt. There is what's called the twin balance sheet problem where, you know,

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:29.280
[Guest]: the banks are indebted, the private sector is indebted. So there is a call for the government

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:36.080
[Guest]: to take that leap forward and invest. Every year, there's some other reason for the governments

00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:40.640
[Guest]: to not cut down on spending as much as they should. But that's what usually happens.

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:46.640
[Guest]: Amit, if I can come in, actually, in the last year's budget, the government had said that

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:53.000
[Guest]: it would stick to the 3% fiscal deficit target. But from the revenue estimates which come

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:58.160
[Guest]: in this year's budget, it shows that they have clearly breached that target that they

00:14:58.160 --> 00:15:03.400
[Guest]: had set for themselves. And even this year, we can expect that they will not be able to

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:10.400
[Guest]: meet the 3% target, it will, like Pawan said, it will go up to 3.5% or even more. And the

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:15.080
[Guest]: biggest thing that we should realize here is that even today, the single largest component

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:20.280
[Guest]: of government spending is actually on interest payments. So this is interest we are paying

00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:28.120
[Guest]: for loans we've accumulated from long back, which means that if this continues, for future

00:15:28.120 --> 00:15:33.600
[Guest]: generations, the government will not be able to spend more on things like health and education,

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:39.280
[Guest]: but a greater component will keep going out as interest payments. That's the biggest problem

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:45.560
[Guest]: why we should be very, very wary of what happens to the fiscal deficit number.

00:15:45.560 --> 00:15:49.640
[Amit Varma]: And that becomes a bit like a vicious circle. And in a sense, you know, the paradox here

00:15:49.640 --> 00:15:53.480
[Amit Varma]: is if you think about the incentives of the politicians involved, the incentive of the

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:58.520
[Amit Varma]: politician is always to win the next election. And a budget is a great opportunity to hand

00:15:58.520 --> 00:16:03.680
[Amit Varma]: out SOPs to this sector or that sector, or this group of vote bank, this group of voters

00:16:03.680 --> 00:16:08.540
[Amit Varma]: or that vote bank, and so on and so forth. And you know, a fiscal deficit that keeps

00:16:08.540 --> 00:16:13.760
[Amit Varma]: growing is essentially a cost that your children have to bear. It's a cost in the future. So

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:17.960
[Amit Varma]: the easiest thing to do, therefore, really, for any government is to kick the can down

00:16:17.960 --> 00:16:22.600
[Amit Varma]: the road and, you know, rationalize having a large fiscal deficit in some way or the

00:16:22.600 --> 00:16:27.560
[Amit Varma]: other, as Pawan pointed out, and, and just spend a lot on appeasing whoever you're trying

00:16:27.560 --> 00:16:28.560
[Guest]: to appease.

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:35.640
[Guest]: Absolutely, Amit. I think the only little discipline that comes in is through various

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:41.420
[Guest]: kinds of ratings of the government. For example, that's why the government of the day is so

00:16:41.420 --> 00:16:47.960
[Guest]: concerned about what Moody's has to say about us, because there is a direct influence on

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:52.880
[Guest]: the cost of borrowing. Because every year the government wants to borrow, there is at

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:58.500
[Guest]: least a little bit of sensitivity to the cost of borrowing today. So that injects the tiny

00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:03.640
[Guest]: amount of discipline or negative incentive over there. And clearly, that is not sufficient

00:17:03.640 --> 00:17:05.160
[Guest]: most of the time.

00:17:05.160 --> 00:17:10.200
[Guest]: If I can come in Amit, this is not a problem unique to India, right? But other countries

00:17:10.200 --> 00:17:15.920
[Guest]: have tried to fix this problem of profligacy through establishment of something called

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:23.480
[Guest]: fiscal councils, like the US has its own CBOs and budgetary office. And then Australia also

00:17:23.480 --> 00:17:29.160
[Guest]: has an arrangement like this. The what they tried to do is this is an independent committee

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:34.840
[Guest]: which tries to keep a track of the promises that government is making. And they try to

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:41.080
[Guest]: come out with estimates to say that, hey, if you have made this promise, do you actually

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:47.720
[Guest]: have the budget for fulfilling this promise or not. And these are reports which are put

00:17:47.720 --> 00:17:52.880
[Guest]: out into the public domain, so that people have better information about the promises

00:17:52.880 --> 00:18:00.220
[Guest]: being made. And it tries to restrict the government officials from going overboard and promising

00:18:00.220 --> 00:18:03.880
[Guest]: things for which money has not been budgeted.

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Speaking of promises being made, Pawan, one of the big promises that has been made in

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:15.640
[Amit Varma]: this budget and that everybody is gung-ho about are, you know, the health guarantees,

00:18:15.640 --> 00:18:22.560
[Amit Varma]: almost sort of people hyping up a future universal health care and so on. But the actual allocations

00:18:22.560 --> 00:18:28.760
[Amit Varma]: in the budget don't reflect the rhetoric of Mr. Jaitley on this.

00:18:28.760 --> 00:18:34.480
[Guest]: Yes, and rhetoric gets lapped up so quickly. There are people who are already calling this

00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:40.520
[Guest]: Modi care, whereas currently it's a couple of sentences in the budget speech. There's

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:45.080
[Guest]: actually very little reflection even in the budget documents. So this idea of a national

00:18:45.080 --> 00:18:51.120
[Guest]: health protection scheme, I think, as Vivek also wrote in Pragati recently, has been bouncing

00:18:51.120 --> 00:18:59.720
[Guest]: around for a while. But what the finance minister essentially promised is that, what, 100 million

00:18:59.720 --> 00:19:06.200
[Guest]: families, that is about 500 million people, will come under this health insurance net

00:19:06.200 --> 00:19:12.200
[Guest]: of some sort, where each family gets a health insurance cover of about five lakh rupees

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:19.280
[Guest]: per year. And this entire thing will be financed by the government of India. And without mentioning

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:23.960
[Guest]: exactly where the money is coming from. As Pranay mentioned earlier, there have been

00:19:23.960 --> 00:19:30.600
[Guest]: tweaks with the SES. So an old education and higher education SES has been renamed as an

00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:36.400
[Guest]: education and health SES. And this has been increased from 3% to 4%. Now the government

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:43.560
[Guest]: estimates an extra 11,000 crores coming in. With 11,000 crores, you can do nothing. With

00:19:43.560 --> 00:19:50.840
[Guest]: 11,000 crores, you're essentially allocating 1,100 rupees per family. And you tell me what

00:19:50.840 --> 00:19:57.760
[Guest]: kind of insurance, health insurance can be available for a full family for just 1,100

00:19:57.760 --> 00:20:03.840
[Guest]: rupees a year. With whatever economies of scale working, they're just much, much smaller

00:20:03.840 --> 00:20:11.880
[Guest]: than what private health insurance costs are in India today. So again, this is a case where

00:20:11.880 --> 00:20:15.840
[Guest]: if India had an independent fiscal council of some sort, they would have fizzed this

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:23.040
[Guest]: themselves. But sitting outside, it's harder to do these estimations on behalf of the government.

00:20:23.040 --> 00:20:31.000
[Guest]: But it's clear that a scheme as grand as this, while perhaps necessary, given that so many

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:39.160
[Guest]: Indians spend for health care out of pocket and often, as a result, slip back into poverty.

00:20:39.160 --> 00:20:45.160
[Guest]: It's just not going to take off because the monies for it are not guaranteed.

00:20:45.160 --> 00:20:51.760
[Amit Varma]: Pranay, one of the balancing acts that a budget often has to pull off is that on the one hand,

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:57.360
[Amit Varma]: it's supposed to be a sign of good governance. But on the other hand, the government in power

00:20:57.360 --> 00:21:03.720
[Amit Varma]: is often more concerned with optics than with governance, especially with elections coming

00:21:03.720 --> 00:21:07.280
[Amit Varma]: up as it happened to be. And this has been a constant criticism of the Modi government

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:11.400
[Amit Varma]: and even I've made it in the past that they care more about optics and governance. Where

00:21:11.400 --> 00:21:17.600
[Amit Varma]: does this budget fall on that, you know, on that difficult question of balancing these?

00:21:17.600 --> 00:21:25.240
[Guest]: Yeah, I think one of the good things that the budget did was basically, finally, there

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:31.160
[Guest]: is a realisation that the government's business is not to be in business. So they are sort

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:37.760
[Guest]: of trying to get do more of divestment. And they have listed up 24 companies which they

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:46.240
[Guest]: plan to divest. So that is sort of trying to reset the balance and earn more revenue

00:21:46.240 --> 00:21:53.200
[Guest]: for the government without taxing people. So that if this gets done, and it will be

00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:59.680
[Guest]: again a politically sensitive move, it would be a move in the right direction.

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:03.840
[Guest]: So but one of the things that is there in almost every budget speech, and it doesn't

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:08.960
[Guest]: really matter which government it is, this government is quite guilty, is that grand

00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:14.840
[Guest]: announcements are made, and the budgetary allocations of it are nowhere near enough.

00:22:14.840 --> 00:22:19.960
[Guest]: So one of the announcements made along with this National Health Protection Scheme was

00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:26.400
[Guest]: a case where the government said that they will start 1.5 lakh wellness centres across

00:22:26.400 --> 00:22:30.800
[Guest]: the country, right. So these are not just primary health centres, but they'll help you

00:22:30.800 --> 00:22:35.640
[Guest]: with diagnostics, primary health, tertiary health, all kinds of magical things. But for

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:41.520
[Guest]: the entire thing, the government has allocated an amount which translates to 80,000 rupees

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:46.240
[Guest]: per centre. Nothing is possible with 80,000, probably they can build the building and keep

00:22:46.240 --> 00:22:50.720
[Guest]: the electricity on and that's about maybe put one person there. And that's all that's

00:22:50.720 --> 00:22:56.720
[Guest]: possible. And this is just one example. There's another where the government talks about,

00:22:56.720 --> 00:23:02.040
[Guest]: you know, how there are these rural hearts of some sort, which should be transformed

00:23:02.040 --> 00:23:08.480
[Guest]: into Grameen Agricultural Markets, whereby, you know, farmers don't have to go 100 kilometres

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:15.880
[Guest]: away or so to sell their wares at an ATMC, but can sell locally. But for these 22,000

00:23:15.880 --> 00:23:21.800
[Guest]: Grameen Agricultural Markets, there is a corpus fund of 200 crores that will be set up. Now,

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:26.200
[Guest]: this is a corpus and you're taking interest on it, you're talking about just 200 crores,

00:23:26.200 --> 00:23:30.560
[Guest]: and you want to use that for 20 plus thousand things. So you're talking about a couple of

00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:36.480
[Guest]: thousand rupees that you can spend per market. So it's these kinds of numbers that beggar

00:23:36.480 --> 00:23:40.120
[Guest]: our belief and you know, they just don't add up.

00:23:40.120 --> 00:23:43.800
[Amit Varma]: And you know, Pranay, one of the points you made in the past, and you've written about

00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:50.080
[Amit Varma]: this for Pragati as well, is, you know, one of your pet suggestions is that the government

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:55.800
[Amit Varma]: should just have 10 centrally sponsored schemes and not the vast numbers that they do now.

00:23:55.800 --> 00:24:00.800
[Amit Varma]: Can you elaborate a little bit on that? And has this budget done anything to address that?

00:24:00.800 --> 00:24:07.920
[Guest]: Yeah, Amit, the budget has not done anything to address that. Actually, with this National

00:24:07.920 --> 00:24:12.600
[Guest]: Health Protection Scheme, in fact, there will be increase in the number of centrally sponsored

00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:20.320
[Guest]: schemes. Why I tried to argue for that was because, see, the constitutional responsibility

00:24:20.320 --> 00:24:26.600
[Guest]: for most of the social sector expenditure actually lies with the states, by which it

00:24:26.600 --> 00:24:33.700
[Guest]: is meant that for anything to do on health or on education, the union government has

00:24:33.700 --> 00:24:38.680
[Guest]: to collaborate with the states. Okay, so even when the union government allots some money,

00:24:38.680 --> 00:24:43.840
[Guest]: it actually first goes to the states and then the state governments implement it. So my

00:24:43.840 --> 00:24:50.120
[Guest]: point was that if state governments are responsible for most of the social sector expenditure,

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:56.520
[Guest]: isn't it better that the union government just gives a lot of money in the form of cash

00:24:56.520 --> 00:25:01.880
[Guest]: to these state governments, and then the state governments decide based on their priorities

00:25:01.880 --> 00:25:08.360
[Guest]: and their preferences where to invest. And this would require government, the union government

00:25:08.360 --> 00:25:13.720
[Guest]: to actually reduce the number of centrally sponsored schemes, where it tries to direct

00:25:13.720 --> 00:25:19.280
[Guest]: that, hey, you should only spend money in this area or not spend in that area. Instead

00:25:19.280 --> 00:25:26.520
[Guest]: of that, the union government can consolidate the expenditure into a couple of areas, health,

00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:32.520
[Guest]: education, defence, etc. and leave the rest of the expenditure as money for the states

00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:38.360
[Guest]: to invest based on their own priorities. So let me wrap it up by asking two questions

00:25:38.360 --> 00:25:46.960
[Amit Varma]: to each of you. The same two questions, Pawan, you go first, which is that, in what ways

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:51.920
[Amit Varma]: has this budget made you happy and disappointed you? That's the first question. And the second

00:25:51.920 --> 00:25:56.840
[Amit Varma]: one is what would you do differently, not in terms of specifics, but in broader directional

00:25:56.840 --> 00:26:04.080
[Guest]: terms? I mean, I really don't know how to be happy at the end of a budget. Sometimes

00:26:04.080 --> 00:26:09.640
[Guest]: the noise seems right, the sound seem right, but you don't really see them backed up with

00:26:09.640 --> 00:26:15.120
[Guest]: the right kind of numbers. And really, after you see a few budgets, there's like a tyranny

00:26:15.120 --> 00:26:20.840
[Guest]: of low expectations, you know, so it can be bad, or it can be truly abysmal and horrible.

00:26:20.840 --> 00:26:29.200
[Guest]: And there's really nothing else. In terms of what I would recommend would be done differently,

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:35.280
[Guest]: is we need to fundamentally reform the budgeting system and process. It's high time that the

00:26:35.280 --> 00:26:40.760
[Guest]: Government of India not adopt standards that, you know, it imposes on the rest of us, we

00:26:40.760 --> 00:26:46.080
[Guest]: need accrual accounting. The government thing is not just about cash coming in and going

00:26:46.080 --> 00:26:51.080
[Guest]: out, but about assets and liabilities that the government has, and how best it's utilizing

00:26:51.080 --> 00:26:57.840
[Guest]: them and how best it's managing them. So I think we need to go beyond just this cash

00:26:57.840 --> 00:27:03.960
[Guest]: accounting that we have and talk about, you know, the Indian state or the country of India

00:27:03.960 --> 00:27:10.600
[Guest]: has a certain amount of wealth, some portion of it is owned by the government, the India

00:27:10.600 --> 00:27:16.120
[Guest]: as a society has debts too, and some of it is with the government. And we really need

00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:23.160
[Guest]: to be starting to talk and think about that rather than, is it 24.4 lakh crores or 25.

00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:24.160
[Guest]: Pranay?

00:27:24.160 --> 00:27:31.440
[Guest]: Yeah, Amit, I think one thing that disappointed me was basically, the elephant in the room

00:27:31.440 --> 00:27:39.600
[Guest]: really is the lack of jobs in India. And I don't think there's enough in the budget where

00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:45.480
[Guest]: things are being done to see this as an emergency right now. So the way the government is trying

00:27:45.480 --> 00:27:52.880
[Guest]: to do things is saying that we will increase customs duties on electronics, and they explicitly

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:57.400
[Guest]: say that this will increase jobs, because our industries will become more competitive.

00:27:57.400 --> 00:28:03.520
[Guest]: Now, this is good old style import substitution. And this is in no way going to increase jobs.

00:28:03.520 --> 00:28:08.320
[Guest]: In fact, it is going to hurt our industries, because we anyways import things from outside,

00:28:08.320 --> 00:28:13.920
[Guest]: we don't produce some of the things which go into electronics. So these are small things

00:28:13.920 --> 00:28:19.240
[Guest]: which the government is trying to do and say that doing such things will help us increase

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:27.280
[Guest]: jobs. But the bigger question of increasing economic growth, facilitating smaller companies

00:28:27.280 --> 00:28:32.280
[Guest]: to grow such that and also creating bigger companies so that they can provide jobs at

00:28:32.280 --> 00:28:38.240
[Guest]: a larger scale, are things that are still left untouched. So that is sort of disappointing.

00:28:38.240 --> 00:28:43.360
[Guest]: And if I were given a chance, as I said, I would just reduce the number of schemes that

00:28:43.360 --> 00:28:49.400
[Guest]: the government of India runs and give a lot more freedom to the states in implementing

00:28:49.400 --> 00:28:52.640
[Guest]: these government expenditures.

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:59.560
[Guest]: You know, if I can go one step from what Pranay said, I think it's time to end a lot of government

00:28:59.560 --> 00:29:03.560
[Guest]: of India departments. India does not need a Ministry of Health, we don't really need

00:29:03.560 --> 00:29:08.200
[Guest]: a Ministry of Human Resource Development. We might need other centres, other bodies

00:29:08.200 --> 00:29:11.520
[Guest]: there instead of those ministries, but they're not necessary.

00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:16.840
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely. And to cycle back to what you said earlier, Pranay, that supposing you expected

00:29:16.840 --> 00:29:23.320
[Amit Varma]: the government to signal its concern for the jobs crisis that is already upon us, what

00:29:23.320 --> 00:29:26.000
[Amit Varma]: could it have done differently in this budget?

00:29:26.000 --> 00:29:34.240
[Guest]: Amit, the thing that could be done differently is basically reforming the factor markets,

00:29:34.240 --> 00:29:43.440
[Guest]: basically changing how land, labour etc. can exchange hands is the big deal here. And that

00:29:43.440 --> 00:29:48.400
[Guest]: has been written about ad nauseum by lots of people about how India needs to reform

00:29:48.400 --> 00:29:52.920
[Guest]: these factor markets. Unless that is done, we are only talking about tweaking at the

00:29:52.920 --> 00:29:57.760
[Guest]: margins and we'll not be able to create jobs at a bigger scale.

00:29:57.760 --> 00:29:59.720
[Guest]: Thanks a lot for coming on the show, guys.

00:29:59.720 --> 00:30:00.720
[Guest]: Thank you.

00:30:00.720 --> 00:30:30.680
[Amit Varma]: Thanks, Amit.

00:30:30.720 --> 00:30:59.880
[Amit Varma]: Thanks, Pranay.

